{"title_page": "Comic book archive", "text_new": "{{short description|File format}}\n{{Infobox file format\n| name                   = Comic book archive file\n| icon                   = \n| logo                   = \n| screenshot             = WikiPhone003.png \n| caption                = Comic book archives may be accessed via [[Tablet computer|tablets]] or [[iPhones]].\n| extension              = <code>.cbr, .cbz, .cbt, .cba, .cb7</code> (containers)\n|_noextcode              = y\n| mime                   = application/vnd.comicbook+zip [.cbz only], application/vnd.comicbook-rar [.cbr only]\n| type code              = \n| uniform type           = \n| magic                  = \n| owner                  = \n| released               = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|mm|dd|df=yes/no}} -->\n| latest release version = \n| latest release date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|mm|dd|df=yes/no}} -->\n| genre                  = [[Multimedia]], [[archive file]]\n| container for          = Images\n| contained by           = \n| extended from          = \n| extended to            = \n| standard               = None\n| free                   = \n| url                    = \n}}\nA '''comic book archive''' or '''comic book reader file''' (also called '''sequential image file''') is a type of [[archive file]] for the purpose of sequential viewing of images, commonly for [[comic book]]s. The idea was made popular by the [[CDisplay]] sequential image viewer;<ref>[http://download.cnet.com/CDisplay-Image-Display/3000-18488_4-10162238.html CDisplay Image Display] Download.com</ref> since then, many viewers for different platforms have been created.\n\n== Design ==\nComic book archive files mainly consist of a series of [[image file]]s with specific naming, typically [[Portable Network Graphics|PNG]] ([[lossless compression]]) or [[JPEG]] ([[lossy compression]]) files, stored as a single [[archive file]]. Occasionally [[GIF]], [[Windows and OS/2 bitmap|BMP]], and [[Tagged Image File Format|TIFF]] files are seen. Folders may be used to group images. Also it can contain optional metadata stored as [[XML]] file, but there's no open format or DTD schema for it. \n\nThe [[filename extension]] indicates the archive type used:\n* .cb7 \u2192 [[7z]]\n* .cba \u2192 [[ACE (compression file format)|ACE]]\n* .cbr \u2192 [[RAR (file format)|RAR]]<ref>{{cite web|title=CBR file extension|url=http://www.fileinfo.com/extension/cbr|accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n* .cbt \u2192 [[tar (file format)|TAR]]\n* .cbz \u2192 [[ZIP (file format)|ZIP]]<ref>{{cite web|title=CBZ file extension|url=http://www.fileinfo.com/extension/cbz|accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nComic book archive files are not a distinct file format; only the file name extension differs from a standard file of the given archive type.\n\nComic book archive viewers typically offer various dedicated functions to read the content, like one page forward/backwards, go to first/last page, zoom or print. Some applications support additional tag information in the form of embedded XML files in the archive or use of the ZIP comment to store additional information.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://code.google.com/p/comicbookinfo/ | title = Metadata for Digital Comics }}</ref>{{Dead link|date=March 2020}} These files can include additional information like artists, story information, table of contents or even a separate text layer for comic book translations.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://launchpad.net/acbf | title = Advanced Comic Book Format project page }}</ref>\n\n== Adoption ==\n\n===Windows===\n* [[Calibre (software)|Calibre]] e-book reader can view and convert comic archives to different formats, but does not handle .cbr or .cb7 formats.\n* [[CDisplay]] was the first application to support the CBR format.\n* CDisplayEx inspired by [[CDisplay]] with additional viewing features.\n* [[Comic Seer (Desktop)]] is a comic book archive viewer and organizer for the desktop.\n* [[Gonvisor]] is a comic reader simple to use with some features to improve image quality.\n* [[STDU Viewer]]\n* [[SumatraPDF]]\n\n===Mac===\n* [[Calibre (software)|Calibre]] can view and convert to different formats.\n* [[Simple Comic]], an open source comic viewer with many features including archive reading support.\n\n===iOS===\n* [[Panels]] the best comic reader for iOS. Supports PDF/CBR/CBZ and can import comics from multiple sources. Supports Ubooquity and panel by panel navigation.\n\n===Android=== \n* [[FBReader]] supports CBZ/CBR files on Android via the ComicBook plugin available from its website.<ref>{{cite web |title=FBReader ComicBook plugin|url=https://fbreader.org/content/fbreader-comicbook-plugin |website=FBReader}}</ref>\n* Moon+ Reader supports CBZ and CBR files.\n* Readler can read CBZ/CBR files ad-free.\n\n===Unix-like===\n* [[Calibre (software)|Calibre]] can view and convert to different formats.\n* [[Comic Seer (Desktop)]] is a comic book archive viewer and organizer for the desktop.\n* [[Evince]] document viewer, includes support for the format.\n* [[Okular]] can view many formats, including PDF and CBR, and is included in the [[KDE Software Compilation]].\n* [[MuPDF]] is a cross-platform lightweight PDF, XPS, and E-book viewer.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Comparison of image viewers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{dmoz|Computers/Software/Graphics/Viewers/Comic_Book_Files}}\n\n{{Ebooks}} <!--navbox-->\n\n[[Category:Computer file formats]]\n[[Category:E-books]]\n[[Category:Comics formats]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|File format}}\n{{Infobox file format\n| name                   = Comic book archive file\n| icon                   = \n| logo                   = \n| screenshot             = WikiPhone003.png \n| caption                = Comic book archives may be accessed via [[Tablet computer|tablets]] or [[iPhones]].\n| extension              = <code>.cbr, .cbz, .cbt, .cba, .cb7</code> (containers)\n|_noextcode              = y\n| mime                   = application/vnd.comicbook+zip [.cbz only], application/vnd.comicbook-rar [.cbr only]\n| type code              = \n| uniform type           = \n| magic                  = \n| owner                  = \n| released               = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|mm|dd|df=yes/no}} -->\n| latest release version = \n| latest release date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|mm|dd|df=yes/no}} -->\n| genre                  = [[Multimedia]], [[archive file]]\n| container for          = Images\n| contained by           = \n| extended from          = \n| extended to            = \n| standard               = None\n| free                   = \n| url                    = \n}}\nA '''comic book archive''' or '''comic book reader file''' (also called '''sequential image file''') is a type of [[archive file]] for the purpose of sequential viewing of images, commonly for [[comic book]]s. The idea was made popular by the [[CDisplay]] sequential image viewer;<ref>[http://download.cnet.com/CDisplay-Image-Display/3000-18488_4-10162238.html CDisplay Image Display] Download.com</ref> since then, many viewers for different platforms have been created.\n\n== Design ==\nComic book archive files mainly consist of a series of [[image file]]s with specific naming, typically [[Portable Network Graphics|PNG]] ([[lossless compression]]) or [[JPEG]] ([[lossy compression]]) files, stored as a single [[archive file]]. Occasionally [[GIF]], [[Windows and OS/2 bitmap|BMP]], and [[Tagged Image File Format|TIFF]] files are seen. Folders may be used to group images. Also it can contain optional metadata stored as [[XML]] file, but there's no open format or DTD schema for it. \n\nThe [[filename extension]] indicates the archive type used:\n* .cb7 \u2192 [[7z]]\n* .cba \u2192 [[ACE (compression file format)|ACE]]\n* .cbr \u2192 [[RAR (file format)|RAR]]<ref>{{cite web|title=CBR file extension|url=http://www.fileinfo.com/extension/cbr|accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n* .cbt \u2192 [[tar (file format)|TAR]]\n* .cbz \u2192 [[ZIP (file format)|ZIP]]<ref>{{cite web|title=CBZ file extension|url=http://www.fileinfo.com/extension/cbz|accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nComic book archive files are not a distinct file format; only the file name extension differs from a standard file of the given archive type.\n\nComic book archive viewers typically offer various dedicated functions to read the content, like one page forward/backwards, go to first/last page, zoom or print. Some applications support additional tag information in the form of embedded XML files in the archive or use of the ZIP comment to store additional information.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://code.google.com/p/comicbookinfo/ | title = Metadata for Digital Comics }}</ref>{{Dead link|date=March 2020}} These files can include additional information like artists, story information, table of contents or even a separate text layer for comic book translations.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://launchpad.net/acbf | title = Advanced Comic Book Format project page }}</ref>\n\n== Adoption ==\n\n===Windows===\n* [[Calibre (software)|Calibre]] e-book reader can view and convert comic archives to different formats, but does not handle .cbr or .cb7 formats.\n* [[CDisplay]] was the first application to support the CBR format.\n* CDisplayEx inspired by [[CDisplay]] with additional viewing features.\n* [[Comic Seer (Desktop)]] is a comic book archive viewer and organizer for the desktop.\n* [[Gonvisor]] is a comic reader simple to use with some features to improve image quality.\n* [[STDU Viewer]]\n* [[SumatraPDF]]\n\n===Mac===\n* [[Calibre (software)|Calibre]] can view and convert to different formats.\n* [[Simple Comic]], an open source comic viewer with many features including archive reading support.\n\n===Android=== \n* [[FBReader]] supports CBZ/CBR files on Android via the ComicBook plugin available from its website.<ref>{{cite web |title=FBReader ComicBook plugin|url=https://fbreader.org/content/fbreader-comicbook-plugin |website=FBReader}}</ref>\n* Moon+ Reader supports CBZ and CBR files.\n* Readler can read CBZ/CBR files ad-free.\n\n===Unix-like===\n* [[Calibre (software)|Calibre]] can view and convert to different formats.\n* [[Comic Seer (Desktop)]] is a comic book archive viewer and organizer for the desktop.\n* [[Evince]] document viewer, includes support for the format.\n* [[Okular]] can view many formats, including PDF and CBR, and is included in the [[KDE Software Compilation]].\n* [[MuPDF]] is a cross-platform lightweight PDF, XPS, and E-book viewer.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Comparison of image viewers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{dmoz|Computers/Software/Graphics/Viewers/Comic_Book_Files}}\n\n{{Ebooks}} <!--navbox-->\n\n[[Category:Computer file formats]]\n[[Category:E-books]]\n[[Category:Comics formats]]\n", "name_user": "70.95.168.210", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAdoption)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comic_book_archive"}
